Project Python Foundations: FoodHub Data Analysis

Context

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost_of_the_order: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

# --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# REMAINING CATEGORICAL VARIABLES AND NUMERIC VARIABLES
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Set visualization style for all Seaborn plots
sns.set(style="whitegrid")

# rcParams (runtime configuration parameters) store default settings for all Matplotlib plots.
# Here, we set the default figure size for all plots to 10 inches wide and 4 inches tall
# unless overridden in plt.figure(figsize=(...)).
plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = (10,4)

# Create a list for numeric columns and categorical columns.
numeric_cols = ['cost_of_the_order', 'food_preparation_time', 'delivery_time']
categorical_cols = ['restaurant_name', 'cuisine_type', 'day_of_the_week', 'rating']

# --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CATEGORICAL VARIABLES
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Loop through each categorical column in the dataset
for col in categorical_cols:

    # Print a header to clearly show which column is being analyzed
    header = f"{col.upper()} - CATEGORICAL COLUMN ANALYSIS"
    # centers your header text inside a 100-character-wide space, padded with - on both sides.
    print("\n" + header.center(130, "-") + "\n")

    # Display the frequency of each category.
    # value_counts() returns the count of unique categories in descending order (highest count first).
    # The index represents each unique category, and the corresponding value shows how many times it appears.
    # This helps identify which categories (like restaurants, cuisines, etc.) occur most often in the dataset.
    print(f"Frequency of each unique category in descending order (highest count first) for {col}:")
    print("------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------")
    vc = df[col].value_counts()
    print(vc, "\n")

    # ---------------------------------------------------------
    # restaurant_name  Skew & low-order restaurant check
    # ---------------------------------------------------------
    if col == 'restaurant_name':
        total_restaurants = vc.count()
        few_orders = vc[vc <= 3].count()
        pct_few = (few_orders / total_restaurants) * 100
        pct_many = 100 - pct_few

        print(f"Total unique restaurants: {total_restaurants}")
        print(f"Restaurants with  3 orders: {few_orders} ({pct_few:.1f}%)")
        print(f"Remaining restaurants handling majority of orders: {pct_many:.1f}%\n")

    # ---------------------------------------------------------
    # cuisine_type  Find most popular & least popular cuisines
    # ---------------------------------------------------------
    elif col == 'cuisine_type':
        total_cuisines = vc.count()
        top_cuisine = vc.idxmax()
        top_count = vc.max()
        top_pct = (top_count / df.shape[0]) * 100

        print(f"Total unique cuisines: {total_cuisines}")
        print(f"Most popular cuisine: {top_cuisine} ({top_count} orders, {top_pct:.1f}% of total orders)\n")

    # ---------------------------------------------------------
    # day_of_the_week  Compare weekday vs weekend volume
    # ---------------------------------------------------------
    elif col == 'day_of_the_week':
        total_orders = df.shape[0]
        day_percentages = (vc / total_orders) * 100
        print("Percentage of orders by day category:\n")
        print(day_percentages.round(2).astype(str))

        weekend_share = day_percentages.get('Weekend', 0)
        weekday_share = day_percentages.get('Weekday', 0)
        print(f"Weekend orders: {weekend_share:.1f}% | Weekday orders: {weekday_share:.1f}%\n")

    # ------------------------------------------------------------------
    # rating  Handle 'Not given' and rated orders separately
    # ------------------------------------------------------------------
    elif col == 'rating':
        total_orders = df.shape[0]
        not_rated_count = vc.get('Not given', 0)
        rated_orders = total_orders - not_rated_count
        pct_not_rated = (not_rated_count / total_orders) * 100

        print(f"Total orders: {total_orders}\n")
        print(f"Orders with 'Not given' rating: {not_rated_count} ({pct_not_rated:.2f}%)")

        if rated_orders > 0:
            rated_only = df[df['rating'] != 'Not given']['rating'].value_counts(normalize=True) * 100
            print("\nPercentage distribution among rated orders:(excluding 'Not given' rating)")
            print("--------------------------------------------------------------------------")
            print(rated_only.round(2).astype(str) + '%')
        print("\n")

    # Create a new figure for each categorical variable
    # figsize=(10, 4) sets the overall size of the figure  10 inches wide and 4 inches tall.
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,4))

    # Create a countplot to visualize the frequency of categories
    # y=df[col] -> plots category names on the Y-axis (horizontal bars)
    # order=df[col].value_counts().index[:10] -> shows the top 10 most frequent categories in descending order
    # hue=df[col] -> assigns each category a different color (to avoid the Seaborn deprecation warning)
    # palette="crest" -> applies a nice gradient color palette
    # legend=False -> hides the redundant legend since category names are already on the Y-
    # Visualization - Top 10 of each unqiue categories for current column
    sns.countplot(y=df[col], order=df[col].value_counts().index[:10], hue=df[col], palette="crest", legend=False)

     # Add a descriptive title for each plot
    plt.title(f"Top 10 Categories in {col}")

    # Label the X-axis and Y-axis for clarity
    plt.xlabel("Count")  # X-axis = number of occurrences/count
    plt.ylabel(col)      # Y-axis = category name (e.g., restaurant_name or cuisine_type)

    # Display the plot
    plt.show()

# --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# NUMERIC VARIABLES
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Loop through each numerical column in the dataset
for col in numeric_cols:

    # print a header to identify which column is being analyzed
    header = f"{col.upper()} - NUMERICAL COLUMN ANALYSIS"
    # centers your header text inside a 100-character-wide space, padded with - on both sides.
    print("\n" + header.center(130, "-") + "\n")

    # Display descriptive statistics (count, mean, std, min, quartiles, max) for numeric variables.
    # Descriptive statistics summarize and describe the main features of a dataset,
    # helping you quickly understand its center (mean/median(50%)), spread (std/IQR), and range,
    # without examining every individual data point.
    print(f"Descriptive statistics summary for numeric columns: {col}\n")
    print(df[col].describe().T)

    # --------------------------------------------------------------
    # Create side-by-side visualizations: Histogram + Boxplot
    # --------------------------------------------------------------

    # the subplots() function creates an empty figure containing 1 row and 2 columns of subplots
    # two plots placed side by side for easy comparison.
    # for each column analyzed: the left side shows the histogram with a KDE curve,
    # and the right side shows the boxplot for the same column.
    # fig is the overall figure object (the entire canvas).
    # figsize=(12, 4) this sets the size of the entire figure  not each individual plot.
    # 'axes' is an array of two subplot objects:
    #   axes[0]  the left subplot (first plot)
    #   axes[1]  the right subplot (second plot)
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 4))

    print(f"\n\033[1m VISUALIZE SIDE-BY-SIDE: Histogram + Boxplot for {header}\033[0m \n")

    # --- Plot 1: Histogram (left subplot) ---
    # A histogram shows how the data is distributed (frequency of values).
    # Bars represent actual data counts  how many data points fall into each range (bin).
    # 'kde=True' adds a smooth density curve (a line over the bars).
    # that shows the overall shape of the data distribution.
    # The line makes it easier to see and understand whether the data is:
    #   - Symmetric (bell-shaped)
    #   - Right-skewed (tail to the right)
    #   - Left-skewed (tail to the left)
    sns.histplot(df[col], kde=True, ax=axes[0], color="teal")

    #Adds a title to the first plot.
    axes[0].set_title(f"Histogram of {col}")

    # --- Plot 2: Boxplot (right subplot) ---
    # create a boxplot for numeric column (df[col]) in the second subplot (axes[1]).
    # A boxplot visualizes the median, quartiles, interquartile range (IQR), and potential outliers.
    # The box represents the middle 50% of the data (IQR).
    # The line inside the box is the median, and points beyond the whiskers represent outliers.
    # This plot helps identify the data spread, variability, and skewness.
    sns.boxplot(x=df[col], ax=axes[1], color="lightgreen", showfliers=True)
    axes[1].set_title(f"Boxplot of {col}")

    # Calculate quartile, IQR, and outlier boundaries
    q1 = df[col].quantile(0.25)
    median = df[col].median()
    q3 = df[col].quantile(0.75)

    # Add text annotations for Q1, median, and Q3 on the plot
    # axes[1].text(x, y, text, ...)  writes text at position (x, y):
    # x -> the numeric value (Q1, median, or Q3).
    # y -> a small offset (like 0.05 or 0.08) to place it slightly above the box.
    # ha='center' -> horizontally center the label above the respective line.
    # fontsize and color for readability.
    axes[1].text(q1, 0.05, f"Q1 = {q1:.2f}", ha='center', color='teal', fontsize=9)
    axes[1].text(median, 0.12, f"Median = {median:.2f}", ha='center', color='darkblue', fontsize=9)
    axes[1].text(q3, 0.05, f"Q3 = {q3:.2f}", ha='center', color='teal', fontsize=9)

    # Optionally, draw a dashed line at the median for emphasis
    axes[1].axvline(median, color='darkblue', linestyle='--', linewidth=1)

    # label the x-axis for clarity
    axes[1].set_xlabel(col)

    # Adjust layout to prevent overlapping labels/titles
    plt.tight_layout()

    # Display both plots
    plt.show()

Observation for Question 6 - Summary of Observations (for individual columns):

  1. order_id (identifier)

    a. All order_id values are unique (unique IDs = total rows), so there are no duplicates.

    b. This column is an identifier only (not a measurable variable) not used for stats like mean/median or distribution plots.

  2. customer_id (identifier)

    a. There are 1,200 unique customers across 1,898 orders, meaning some customers placed multiple orders.

    b. About 36.8% of orders are from repeat customers, showing good customer retention.

    c. Distribution is right-skewed: most customers place only 1 order, some placed 25 orders, and a few customers placed many orders.

    d. Most active customer placed 13 orders.

    e. customer_id is categorical in nature (an integer label), used for grouping/counting, not a numerical variable used for calculations like mean or median.

  3. restaurant_name (categorical)

    a. There are 178 unique restaurants.

    b. Distribution is highly skewed (long tail): a few restaurants receive most of the orders, while most of the restaurants have very few orders.

    c. Around 54% of restaurants have three or fewer orders, while the remaining 46% handle the majority of total order volume.

    d. Top-performing restaurants include Shake Shack (219), The Meatball Shop (132), Blue Ribbon Sushi (119).

    Implication: Focus marketing and app promotions on two groups:

    (i) Top-performing restaurants Work closely with the restaurants that already get the most orders. Give them more visibility in the app and run joint marketing campaigns to maintain their momentum and further increase engagement and revenue.

# Question 9: What percentage of the orders cost more than $20?

# Step 1: Count the total number of orders in the dataset
# len(df) returns the total number of rows (each row = one order)
total_orders = len(df)

# Step 2: Count how many orders have a cost greater than $20
# df['cost_of_the_order'] > 20 creates a Boolean filter (True for orders > $20)
# df[...] applies this filter to return only rows where the condition is True
# shape[0] gives the number of such rows (count of orders > $20)
orders_above_20 = df[df['cost_of_the_order'] > 20].shape[0]

# Step 3: Calculate the percentage of orders costing more than $20
# Divide the count of expensive orders by total orders and multiply by 100 to get %
percentage_above_20 = (orders_above_20 / total_orders) * 100

# Step 4: Display the results
print(f"Total Orders: {total_orders}")
print(f"Orders costing more than $20: {orders_above_20}")
print(f"Percentage of orders costing more than $20: {percentage_above_20:.2f}%")

Question 13: The company wants to provide a promotional offer in the advertisement of the restaurants. The condition to get the offer is that the restaurants must have a rating count of more than 50 and the average rating should be greater than 4. Find the restaurants fulfilling the criteria to get the promotional offer. [3 marks]

In[107]:
# Question 13: Find restaurants eligible for promotional offer

# Criteria Condition:
#   - Restaurant must have more than 50 ratings (count > 50)
#   - Average rating must be greater than 4

# Step 1: Exclude non-numeric ratings ("Not given")
# The 'rating' column contains text values like 'Not given' along with numeric ratings.
# These need to be removed before performing numeric operations.
# filter (Filter Non-Numeric Ratings) + copy() to ensures safe modification (no warning).
df_filtered = df.loc[df['rating'] != 'Not given', ['restaurant_name', 'rating']].copy()

# Step 2: Convert the 'rating' column from string to integer
# This allows us to calculate averages and counts numerically.
df_filtered['rating'] = df_filtered['rating'].astype(int)

# Step 3: Group the dataset by 'restaurant_name' and compute:
#   - 'count'  number of ratings each restaurant received
#   - 'mean'   average rating for each restaurant
# The result is a new DataFrame with restaurant names and their rating stats.
# Groups data by restaurant. Calculates both count (number of ratings) and mean (average rating).
restaurant_rating_stats = df_filtered.groupby('restaurant_name')['rating'].agg(['count', 'mean']).reset_index()

# Step 4: Apply the eligibility conditions for the promotional offer:
#   - count > 50  restaurant must have more than 50 ratings
#   - mean > 4    average rating must be greater than 4
# Filters only those restaurants with more than 50 ratings and average rating above 4.
eligible_restaurants = restaurant_rating_stats[
    (restaurant_rating_stats['count'] > 50) &
    (restaurant_rating_stats['mean'] > 4)
]

# Step 5: Display the result
print("\n Restaurants eligible for promotional offer:")
print(eligible_restaurants)

# Step 6 (Optional): Visualize eligible restaurants by their average rating
# sns.barplot() creates a horizontal bar chart showing eligible restaurants and their average ratings.
# hue='restaurant_name' ensures each restaurant has a unique color and avoids the palette deprecation warning.
plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
sns.barplot(
    x='mean',
    y='restaurant_name',
    hue='restaurant_name',
    data=eligible_restaurants,
    palette="crest",
    legend=False
)
# Add titles and labels for clarity
plt.title('Restaurants Eligible for Promotional Offer')
plt.xlabel('Average Rating')
plt.ylabel('Restaurant Name')

# Show the plot
plt.show()

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders. [3 marks]

In[108]:
# Question 14: Net revenue generated by the company (without modifying original DataFrame)

# Commission logic:
#   - 25% commission on orders costing > $20
#   - 15% commission on orders costing > $5 and <= $20
#   - 0% commission on orders costing  $5

# Step 1: Apply conditional commission logic using np.where()
# Instead of modifying df, store results in a separate variable 'commission'.
commission = np.where(
    df['cost_of_the_order'] > 20,
    0.25 * df['cost_of_the_order'],      # 25% for orders > $20
    np.where(
        df['cost_of_the_order'] > 5,
        0.15 * df['cost_of_the_order'],  # 15% for orders > $5 and  $20
        0                                # 0% for orders  $5
    )
)

# Step 2: Calculate total net revenue
# The company's revenue = sum of all commissions across all orders.
net_revenue = commission.sum()
print(f"Net revenue generated by the company across all orders: ${net_revenue:.2f}\n")

# Step 3: Sanity Check  Recalculate revenue by order groups
# This confirms that the commission logic is applied correctly.

# Group 1: High-value orders (> $20)
high_value_orders = df[df['cost_of_the_order'] > 20]

# Group 2: Mid-value orders ($5 < order  $20)
mid_value_orders = df[(df['cost_of_the_order'] > 5) & (df['cost_of_the_order'] <= 20)]

# Group 3: Low-value orders ( $5)
low_value_orders = df[df['cost_of_the_order'] <= 5]

# Calculate revenue separately for both segments
revenue_high = (0.25 * high_value_orders['cost_of_the_order']).sum()
revenue_mid = (0.15 * mid_value_orders['cost_of_the_order']).sum()

# Combine to verify total net_revenue
net_revenue_check = revenue_high + revenue_mid

# Step 4: Sanity Check : Display revenue breakdown for validation
print("\nRevenue breakdown by order category:")
print("--------------------------------------")
print(f"1. Revenue from >$20 orders: ${revenue_high:.2f}")
print(f"2. Revenue from $5$20 orders: ${revenue_mid:.2f}")
print(f"3. Total Net Revenue: ${net_revenue_check:.2f}")

# Step 5: Validation check  ensure both total net_revenue match
# Using np.isclose() to handle minor rounding differences
if np.isclose(net_revenue, net_revenue_check):
    print("4. Validation passed  Both total net_revenue match.")
else:
    print("4. Validation failed  total net_revenue do not match.")

# Question 15: Percentage of orders taking more than 60 minutes in total (non-destructive)

# Step 1: Calculate total time taken per order (without adding a new column)
# Instead of saving to df['total_time'], store the result in a temporary variable.
total_time = df['food_preparation_time'] + df['delivery_time']

# Step 2: Count total number of orders in the dataset
total_orders = len(df)  # total rows

# Step 3: Count how many orders took more than 60 minutes in total
# Create a Boolean mask (True for orders > 60 minutes)
orders_above_60 = (total_time > 60).sum()  # sum() counts True values

# Step 4: Calculate the percentage of such orders
percentage_above_60 = (orders_above_60 / total_orders) * 100

# Step 5: Display results
print(f"Total Orders: {total_orders}")
print(f"Orders taking more than 60 minutes: {orders_above_60}")
print(f"Percentage of orders taking more than 60 minutes: {percentage_above_60:.2f}%")

# Question 16: Mean delivery time comparison between weekdays and weekends

# Step 1: Group the data by 'day_of_the_week' and calculate the average delivery time.
# The result shows the mean delivery time for each category  'Weekday' and 'Weekend'.
mean_delivery_by_day = df.groupby('day_of_the_week')['delivery_time'].mean().reset_index()

# Step 2: Display the mean delivery time for both day types.
print("Mean Delivery Time by Day Type:")
print("-------------------------------")
print(mean_delivery_by_day)
print("\n")

# Example output:
#   day_of_the_week   delivery_time
#   Weekday           28.34
#   Weekend           22.47
# This shows deliveries are faster on weekends.

# Step 3: Visualize the difference between weekday and weekend mean delivery times.

# sns.barplot() draws bars comparing mean delivery times between weekday and weekend.
# hue='day_of_the_week'  ensures each bar gets a unique color.
# palette='viridis'  applies a nice gradient color scheme.
# legend=False  removes the redundant legend since labels already appear on X-axis.
plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
sns.barplot(
    x='day_of_the_week',
    y='delivery_time',
    hue='day_of_the_week',
    data=mean_delivery_by_day,
    palette='viridis',
    legend=False
)

# Step 4: Add title and labels for clarity.
plt.title('Mean Delivery Time: Weekday vs Weekend')
plt.xlabel('Day of the Week')
plt.ylabel('Mean Delivery Time (minutes)')

# Step 5: Show the plot.
plt.show()
